Speech Analytics and Sentiment Intelligence
One of the most underutilized yet powerful technologies demonstrated at CES 2026 is advanced speech analytics powered by natural language processing (NLP). Moving beyond simple keyword spotting, modern speech analytics platforms can analyze tone, emotion, stress levels, and customer satisfaction indicators throughout every conversation.

These insights serve multiple purposes. For quality management, supervisors can identify calls that require coaching based on communication style, empathy demonstration, and compliance adherence. For customer retention, the system can flag conversations where customers express frustration or dissatisfaction, enabling immediate escalation or follow-up outreach. For product development, aggregated speech analytics data reveals customer pain points, feature requests, and competitive commentary that informs product strategy.

The application of sentiment analysis has proven particularly valuable. Organizations implementing comprehensive sentiment analysis report a 31% improvement in Net Promoter Score (NPS) and a 19% reduction in customer churn. The technology doesn't just monitor sentiment in the moment; it tracks sentiment trends over time, helping organizations identify systemic issues that require operational or strategic adjustments.

Emerging Technologies Reshaping Contact Centers
Beyond AI, cloud, and omnichannel, several emerging technologies showcased at CES 2026 are beginning to reshape contact center possibilities. These technologies represent the next frontier of customer engagement innovation, and early adopters are already gaining significant competitive advantages.

Voice-activated AI and smart speakers: The integration of contact center capabilities into voice-activated ecosystems is accelerating. Customers can initiate support requests through Alexa, Google Home, or proprietary voice assistants, with the system intelligently routing to human agents when necessary. This creates opportunities for proactive support a smart device might detect an issue with a connected appliance and automatically initiate a support conversation before the customer even realizes there's a problem. Voice-first support has increased customer satisfaction scores by an average of 18% in early implementations.

Biometric authentication: Advanced biometric systems are reducing identity verification friction. Voice recognition, facial recognition, and behavioral biometrics enable faster, more secure customer authentication without requiring customers to recite account numbers or answer security questions. Organizations implementing biometric authentication are reducing average handling time by 2-3 minutes per call and dramatically improving security. This technology is particularly valuable in financial services and healthcare, where security is paramount but customer convenience is equally important.

Augmented reality (AR) support: Technical support representatives can now use AR to provide guided assistance to customers. Customers point their smartphone cameras at equipment, and AR overlays provide step-by-step troubleshooting instructions. This is particularly valuable for complex technical issues and has reduced resolution times by an average of 44%. Rather than struggling to explain technical procedures over the phone, customers now see exact instructions overlaid on their physical equipment.

Predictive analytics for customer lifetime value: Advanced customer data platforms (CDPs) are enabling contact centers to make real-time decisions based on customer lifetime value. High-value customers receive priority routing and specialized agents. At-risk customers are identified for proactive retention outreach. This strategic approach to customer segmentation improves both revenue and satisfaction metrics. Progressive organizations have increased customer retention rates by an average of 15% among early adopters.

